post_text: Congratulations Strother FFA and Mr. Randy Bean we appreciate all of your hard work!
shared_text:
Strother FFA
August 31 at 6:47 PM ·

Strother FFA Chapter is one of 32 chapters in the state of Oklahoma to receive the National 3 Star Award! This is the highest honor an FFA chapter can receive at the National level.

The National Chapter Award Program is designed to recognize FFA chapters that actively implement the mission and strategies of the organization. These chapters improve chapter operations using the National Quality Chapter Standards (NQCS) and a Program of Activities (POA) that emphasize growing leaders, building communities and strengthening agriculture. Chapters are rewarded for providing educational experiences for the entire membership.

post_text:
Guideline Update:

Parents/Guardians,

Strother Public School will be requiring masks to be worn by students in grades 6-12 when changing classes. Once they are inside the classroom they will be able to either continue wearing them or take them off. The addition of this protocol will allow us in conjunction with our other protocols to better assist the health department in contact tracing when determining who will be sent to quarantine in the event of a positive case. We are also hopeful this will keep us from having to shut the whole school down in the event of a positive case, due to our ability to contact trace. So we ask that you please send a mask/face covering to school with your students in grades 6-12. I know people will want to debate this, but please don’t on this page. We are trying to put everything we possibly can in place to keep our children safe and our school open. Again we thank you for your assistance in this matter.

Yours In Education

Kolby Johnson
Superintendent

Parents/Guardians

If your child or children are participating in Strother Schools online distance learning program, you will be receiving a letter in the mail shortly. We will be sending you information about where to log in for coursework, student username and password information, student expectations, and teacher information for needed assistance. Strother teachers will be checking on their virtual students twice a week and providing any additional assistance to ensure their academic success, but are always available via email or phone. Thank you for your patience and if you should have any questions please feel free to contact the school at 405-382-4014.

Yours In Education,

Kolby Johnson

post_text:
Thinking about virtual school? Great. Please do not take your kids out of Strother district. When we do that, the district that you enroll in (even if it is an online platform like Epic) gets all of the funding for your child for the entire year.

Go with your district’s virtual plan.
We do not want our local public school to have to suffer and let teachers permanently go for this temporary problem. We have learned a lot about virtual education since March. We have significantly invested in online curriculum and are better prepared to handle distance learning.

Staying enrolled in Strother district insures that the district is still strong when you return to brick and mortar school.

Strother Elementary School was thinking about Strother Elementary School at Strother Public Schools.
May 5 at 8:04 AM · Seminole, OK ·

Pre-K enrollment will be Monday, May 11 and Monday, May 18 from 10:am to 12:00pm. the same time you pick up food. You will need birth certificate, immunizations record, and proof of residency (water bill or electric bill in parents name). Drive up to the Elementary building and stay in your car. We will come out to get papers and make copies and return papers to you.
We are also wanting to find out if a 3 year old program would benefit our community. If you are interested in your child participating in this program please come by the school as well to put your name on the list. If we have enough to start the program we will contact you before the start of school in August.

post_text:
"Oklahoma’s Promise: Alert for 10th-Grade Parents With Recent Income Loss
https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma’s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020, deadline. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

post_text:
The State Board Of Education has suspended in-person instruction for the remainder of the school year. We are deeply saddened for our students but especially for our Seniors. Seniors I want you to know everyone here at Strother loves you and shares in your disappointment that your school year has abruptly ended. Your time here at Strother was treasured by all of our staff and you will be greatly missed. We are still diligently working on a plan to honor you and your accomplishment of graduating high school within the parameters we’ve been mandated to follow. Hopefully we will have that put together in the next few weeks. We have also been instructed to develop some form of distance learning for the remainder of the school year and beginning on April 6, 2020. We have and will be meeting to determine what that will look like for Strother students. We will provide updates and information as it becomes available. Thank you to everyone for your thoughts and prayers during this difficult situation. #StrotherStrong

Yours In Education
Kolby Johnson
Superintendent

post_text:
An emergency meeting of the State Board of Education was held today at 4 pm. State Superintendent, Joy Hofmeister, recommended a state wide shutdown of all schools in the State of Oklahoma until April 6, 2020. The State Board of Education approved her recommendation. So at this time Strother Public Schools will be closed until April 6, 2020. They have communicated to us that we will still be able to serve meals for those students in need, but I’m not sure at this time how that will work or what that looks like. We will continue to work with the State and our Food Service Provider to determine how to move forward. I ask you to remember we are all in uncharted territory at this time and everyone is doing their best for the health and safety of our students. If any changes or updates occur, I will keep you posted.

Yours In Education,

Kolby Johnson
Superintendent

Also please note All Students are not to utilize school facilities during this closure.

post_text:
I just recently participated today in a conference call with the Oklahoma State Superintendent of Schools, Joy Hofmeister, and her staff. At this time the State Superintendent is not recommending statewide school closures, in accordance with information received from the CDC about Covid-19. She suggested closures should be considered when community transmission of the virus from unknown origins occurs. She also informed us that there is a tiered guideline on the CDC’s website to assist schools in trying to determine what is best for their population. (See chart attached, “School Decision Tree”) I will be participating weekly in scheduled conference calls with the State Department of Education on this subject, as well as monitoring daily updates of information concerning the Covid-19 virus. Also, see the attached “Keeping the School Safe Guideline” and help us communicate these safety precautions with your child. We want everyone to enjoy their Spring Break and stay safe.

Yours In Education,

Kolby Johnson
Strother School Superintendent

post_text:
Kindness is an amazing thing....
A photo showing a student's kind gesture to offer up five of his test points to a classmate is getting lots of love on Facebook.

Winston Lee, a history teacher at Letcher County Central High School in Whitesburg, Kentucky, shared a snapshot on Feb. 21 of one of his 11th grader's exams on WWII.
shared_text:
GOODMORNINGAMERICA.COM
Student offers to give test points to classmate with lowest score

K-LOVE Radio News
February 26 at 5:51 AM ·

"One of my guys, a straight A+ guy, offers up his 5 bonus points to someone in need. Anyone. Totally offering up what is rightfully his, his earning, to any peer that may have been struggling especially hard the day of the test."
Lee offered to give five points to students who participated in an exam review game the day before the test. The student who gave away his points had received a grade of 94%. The five points would've increased his score to 99%, but instead they were given to a classmate -- lifting her to a passing grade.

This is Miss Quisenberry’s 5th year of teaching. She teaches Kindergarten. She graduated from East Central University. Her hobbies include watching movies and spending time with family and friends. She especially enjoys spending time with her little sister Keelei. Her favorite color is purple and her favorite book is the Alice in Wonderland. Miss Quisenberry’s favorite subject in school is Reading. Her favorite food is steak, but anything involving bacon or chocolate is on her list too! Her favorite sport is scuba diving. If she wasn’t a teacher she would probably be a Forensics Investigator. Little known fact about Miss Quisenberry, she is currently working toward her Master Degree at ECU and she is a very competitive.
Say a big hello and thank you to Miss Quisenberry at Strother School.

post_text:
This week’s spotlight is on Mr. Dean!
This is Mr. Dean’s 3rd year of teaching. He teaches History and coaches baseball. He graduated from East Central University. His hobbies include softball, boating, hunting and fishing. He also enjoys singing and playing music. His favorite color is blue and his favorite book is The Hobbit by J.R.R. Tolkien. Mr. Dean’s favorite subject in school is History, Western Civilization. His favorite food is pizza and his favorite sport is baseball. If he wasn’t a teacher he would probably be a Doctor of Veterinary Medicine! Mr. Dean is a talented musician and singer with his own band, Cold Water County. If you ever have the chance to see them perform in person, definitely take advantage of the opportunity, you won’t be disappointed. Cool fact about Mr. Dean, he is also a song writer, but he’ll be modest about that. Mr. Dean also has a beautiful dog, Ruger.
Say a big hello and thank you to Mr. Dean at Strother School.

post_text:
Having and finding your voice is difficult for all young students, it seems especially hard for young girls. This is why movements like the #LetsTellHer campaign are so important. One of the things we are doing at Strother School in Mrs. Clark's class is Speaker of the Day. I have watched as students step on to her "Speaker of the Day" stage, their confidence and demeanor change. She is teaching students to be confident and proud, encouraging them to share their story.
As we continue to support girls in finding and using their voices, we encourage you to get involved as well.
As a parent, caregiver, mentor or coach, there are some ways you can encourage the girl in your life to use her voice. There are eight great ways listed in the website below.

https://naaweb.org/professional-development/item/968-8-ways-to-encourage-girls-to-use-their-voices

and

https://www.girlsontherun.org
or on FaceBook- Girls on the Run International

#LetsTellHer

September 27, 2018 at 1:53 PM · Hugo, OK ·

****Welcome to the 4th annual Hugo Pumpkin Festival*****
Come celebrate fall with the elephants and help to benefit their care while making memories with your family. This isn't your typical pumpkin patch.......WE HAVE ELEPHANTS!!!!!! Located at Endangered Ark Foundation, Hugo, OK, one block West of the Intersection of Hwy 93 & East Kirk Road

The fun will last October 4th – 28th
YOUR ADMISSION INCLUDES:
Pumpkin Patch, Hay Mountain, Hayride with the ELEPHANTS, Mystery Maze, Super Slide, Pumpkin Bounce House & Barrel Train Ride!!!!!!
OTHER ATTRACTIONS AVAILABLE:
Zip Line, Kangaroo Air Pillow, , Pony Rides, Giant Obstacle Course, and of course unbelievable photo opportunities.
Don't miss the ALL NEW! Wipe Out Challenge—Dare to beat the challenge!
For Information call (580) 317-8470 or visit www.hugopumpkinfestival.com.
Visit the website for weekly specials!
Proceeds will benefit Endangered Ark Foundation.

Spotlight of the Week!

This week’s spotlight is on Mrs. Votaw!
Mrs. Votaw is a new teacher at Strother. She will be teaching Fourth Grade this year. This is her 5th year of teaching and she graduated from East Central University. She recently married her best friend, Blake Votaw, and they are happy to announce they are expecting their first baby this November! Some of her favorite things are fishing and spending time with her family. Her favorite color is green and her favorite book is “She Said Yes: The Unlikely Martyrdom of Cassie Bernall”. Mrs. Votaw’s favorite subject in school is Math. She is an OU Softball and Football fan as well as an Oklahoma City Thunder fan.
Please help us welcome Mrs. Votaw to our Strother family.

post_text:
Each Week this year we will spotlight a teacher. Our hope is that you will get to know more about our amazing staff. This week’s spotlight is on Mrs. Kornelsen.
Mrs. Kornelsen is a new teacher at Strother. She will be teaching Middle School English this year. She graduated from Oklahoma Baptist University. Some of her favorite things are Mexican food and the color pink. Her favorite books are The Hunger Games Series and of course her favorite subject is English. She enjoys hunting and softball. She is an excellent softball player, I know because she played in a benefit softball tournament this summer. She is married to Ray Kornelsen and they have two little girls Ava, age 7, and Megan, age 3. She enjoys spending time with her family. Please help us welcome Mrs. Kornelsen to our Strother family.
